<h1 class=3D"center">Conversion of Temperature</h1>=20

<div class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/image=
s/thermom.svg" alt=3D"circular thermometer"></div>
<p>There are two main temperature scales:</p>=20
<ul class=3D"dart">=20
	<li><strong>=C2=B0C</strong>, the <b>Celsius Scale</b> (part of the Metric=
 System, used in most countries)</li>=20
	<li><strong>=C2=B0F</strong>, the <b>Fahrenheit Scale</b> (used in the US)=
</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>They both measure the same thing (temperature!), but use different numbe=
rs.</p>=20

<h3 id=3D"tool">Quick Celsius (<strong>=C2=B0C</strong>) / Fahrenheit (<str=
ong>=C2=B0F</strong>) Conversion:</h3>=20

<div style=3D"float:left; margin: 20px 10px 5px 0; width:210px;">=20

<iframe width=3D"100%" height=3D"566px" scrolling=3D"no" title=3D"JavaScrip=
t Animation" style=3D"display: block; margin: auto; border: none; backgroun=
d-color: transparent; overflow: hidden; transition: 0.6s ease-in-out; max-w=
idth: 100%;"></iframe><div class=3D"script" style=3D"height: 560px; display=
: none;"> measure/images/thermometer.js?mode=3Dboxes</div>
</div>=20

<div>=20
<p style=3D" margin-top: 30px;">Type a value in either box</p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<p>Or use the slider</p>=20
<p>Or the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/thermometer.html">I=
nteractive Thermometer</a></p>=20
<p style=3D"min-width:250px;">Or this method:</p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:80px;"><strong>=C2=B0C&nbsp;to&nbs=
p;=C2=B0F</strong></td>
			<td>Divide by 5, then multiply by 9, then add 32</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:80px;"><strong>=C2=B0F&nbsp;to&nbs=
p;=C2=B0C</strong></td>
			<td>Deduct 32, then multiply by 5, then divide by 9</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<p class=3D"center">(<a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/temperature-conv=
ersion.html#explanation">Explanation Below ...</a>)</p>=20
</div>=20

<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>


<h2>Typical Temperatures</h2>=20

<p>(only <b>bold</b> are exactly the same)</p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"width:60px; ">&nbsp;</td>
			<th scope=3D"col" class=3D"center">=C2=B0C</th>
			<th scope=3D"col" class=3D"center">=C2=B0F</th>
			<th scope=3D"col">Description</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"background-color: #ff0000;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">220</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">430</td>
			<td>Hot Oven</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"background-color: #f62734;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">180</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">360</td>
			<td>Moderate Oven</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"background-color: #e4434d;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>100</b></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>212</b></td>
			<td>Water boils</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"background-color: #cf6269;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>40</b></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>104</b></td>
			<td>Hot Bath</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"background-color: #bd7e82;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>37</b></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>98,6</b></td>
			<td>Body temperature</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"background-color: #a89d9d;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>30</b></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>86</b></td>
			<td> Beach weather</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"background-color: #a4a3b0;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">21</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">70</td>
			<td> Room temperature</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"background-color: #a3b8c3;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>10</b></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>50</b></td>
			<td> Cool Day</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"background-color: #a3c5d7;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>0</b></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b> 32</b></td>
			<td> Freezing point of water</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"background-color: #a3cfe7;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=E2=88=9218</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">0</td>
			<td>Very Cold Day</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"background-color: #a2daf8;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>=E2=88=9240</b></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>=E2=88=9240</b></td>
			<td> Extremely Cold Day<br>
(and the same number!)</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<p class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/art/sage=
-pup-front.svg" alt=3D"pup thinks" height=3D"87" width=3D"50"></p>=20


<h2>Some Tricks:</h2>=20

<p>For these three conversions we can "flip the digits" (accurate within 1=
=C2=B0):</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large"><i> =C2=B0C &nbsp; =C2=B0F<br>
28 =E2=87=84 82<br>
16 =E2=87=84 61<br>
04 =E2=87=84 40</i></p>=20
<p>Oven Temperatures in the range 150=C2=B0C to 200=C2=B0C: <b>double =C2=
=B0C to get =C2=B0F</b> (accurate within 8=C2=B0F):</p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table class=3D"center">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td>=C2=B0C</td>
			<td>=C2=B0F<br>
Estimate</td>
			<td><i>=C2=B0F<br>
Actual</i></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>200</td>
			<td>400</td>
			<td><i>392</i></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>180</td>
			<td>360</td>
			<td><i>356</i></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>160</td>
			<td>320</td>
			<td><i>320</i></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>150</td>
			<td>300</td>
			<td><i>302</i></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<p>Going the other way: for the range 300=C2=B0F to 400=C2=B0F we can <b>ha=
lve =C2=B0F to get =C2=B0C</b> (accurate within 4=C2=B0C).</p>=20


<h2 id=3D"explanation">Explanation</h2>=20

<p><b>Celsius</b> and <b>Fahrenheit</b> both measure the same thing (temper=
ature!), but use different numbers:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>Boiling water (at normal pressure) measures <b>100=C2=B0 in Celsius, b=
ut 212=C2=B0 in Fahrenheit</b></li>=20
	<li>And as water freezes it measures <b>0=C2=B0 in Celsius, but 32=C2=B0 i=
n Fahrenheit</b></li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/images/t=
emp-freeze-boil.svg" alt=3D"temperature freeze (0 vs 32) and boil (100 vs 2=
12)" height=3D"400" width=3D"360"></p>=20
<p>Looking at the diagram, notice:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>The scales start at a different number (0 vs 32), so we will need to a=
dd or subtract 32</li>=20
	<li>The scales rise at a different rate (100 vs 180), so we will also need=
 to multiply</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>And so, to convert:</p>=20
<div class=3D"so"> from Celsius to Fahrenheit: first multiply by <span clas=
s=3D"intbl"><em>180</em><strong>100</strong></span>, then add 32</div>
<div class=3D"so"> from Fahrenheit to Celsius: first subtract 32, then mult=
iply by <span class=3D"intbl"><em>100</em><strong>180</strong></span></div>
<div class=3D"clear"></div>
<p><span class=3D"intbl"><em>180</em><strong>100</strong></span> can be sim=
plified to <b><span class=3D"intbl"><em>9</em><strong>5</strong></span></b>=
, and <span class=3D"intbl"><em>100</em><strong>180</strong></span> can be =
simplified to <b><span class=3D"intbl"><em>5</em><strong>9</strong></span><=
/b>, so we get this:</p>=20
<div class=3D"clear">=20
<div class=3D"def center large">=20
<p><strong>=C2=B0C to =C2=B0F:</strong> Divide by 5, then multiply by 9, th=
en add 32</p>=20
<p><strong>=C2=B0F to =C2=B0C:</strong> Subtract 32, then multiply by 5, th=
en divide by 9</p>=20
</div>
</div><br>


<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Convert 25=C2=B0 Celsius <i>(a nice warm day)</i> to Fahrenhe=
it</h3>=20

	<p><i>First:</i> 25=C2=B0 / 5 <em>=3D</em> 5<br>
<i>Then:</i> 5 =C3=97 9 <em>=3D</em> 45<br>
<i>Then:</i> 45 + 32 <em>=3D</em> <b>77=C2=B0F</b></p>=20
	</div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Convert 98,6=C2=B0 Fahrenheit <i>(normal body temperature)</i=
> to Celsius</h3>=20

	<p><i>First:</i> 98,6=C2=B0 =E2=88=92 32 <em>=3D</em> 66,6<br>
<i>Then:</i> 66,6 =C3=97 5 <em>=3D</em> 333<br>
<i>Then:</i> 333 / 9 <em>=3D</em> <b> 37=C2=B0C</b></p>=20
	</div>
<p>We can swap the order of divide and multiply if we want, but don't chang=
e the add or subtract. So this is also OK:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Convert 98,6=C2=B0 Fahrenheit to Celsius (again)</h3>=20

	<p><i>First:</i> 98,6=C2=B0 =E2=88=92 32 <em>=3D</em> 66,6<br>
<i>Then:</i> 66,6 / 9 <em>=3D</em> 7,4<br>
<i>Then:</i> 7,4 =C3=97 5 <em>=3D</em> <b> 37=C2=B0 C</b></p>=20
	<p>(Same answer as before, was it easier or harder this way?)</p>=20
	</div>We can write them as formulas:=20
<div class=3D"def center large">Celsius to Fahrenheit: &nbsp; (=C2=B0C =C3=
=97 <span class=3D"intbl"><em>9</em><strong>5</strong></span>) + 32 <em>=3D=
</em> =C2=B0F<br>
Fahrenheit to Celsius: &nbsp; (=C2=B0F =E2=88=92 32) =C3=97 <span class=3D"=
intbl"><em>5</em><strong>9</strong></span> <em>=3D</em> =C2=B0C</div>&nbsp;=
=20


<h2>Other Methods That Work</h2>=20

<h3>Use 1,8 instead of 9/5</h3>=20

<p>9/5 is equal to 1,8, so we can also use this method:</p>=20
<div class=3D"def center large">Celsius to Fahrenheit: &nbsp; =C2=B0C =C3=
=97 1,8 + 32 <em>=3D</em> =C2=B0F<br>
Fahrenheit to Celsius: &nbsp; (=C2=B0F =E2=88=92 32) / 1,8 <em>=3D</em> =C2=
=B0C</div>
<div class=3D"simple"></div>
<p><br></p>=20
<p>To make "=C3=971,8" easier we can <b>multiply by 2 and subtract 10%</b>,=
 but it only works for =C2=B0C to =C2=B0F:</p>=20
<div class=3D"def center large">Celsius to Fahrenheit: &nbsp; (=C2=B0C =C3=
=97 2) less 10% + 32 <em>=3D</em> =C2=B0F</div>
<div class=3D"simple"></div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Convert 20=C2=B0 Celsius <i>(A nice day)</i> to Fahrenheit</h=
3>=20

	<ul>=20
		<li><b>20</b>x2 <em>=3D</em> 40</li>=20
		<li>less 10% is 40=E2=88=924 <em>=3D</em> 36</li>=20
		<li>36+32 <em>=3D</em> <b>68=C2=B0 F</b></li>=20
	</ul>=20
	</div>
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<h3>Add 40, Multiply, Subtract 40</h3>=20

<p>Since both scales cross at <b>=E2=88=9240=C2=B0</b> (=E2=88=9240=C2=B0 C=
 equals =E2=88=9240=C2=B0 F) we can:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>add 40,</li>=20
	<li>multiply by 5/9 (for =C2=B0F to =C2=B0C), or 9/5 (for =C2=B0C to =C2=
=B0F)</li>=20
	<li>subtract 40</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Like this:</p>=20
<div class=3D"def center large">Celsius to Fahrenheit: &nbsp; Add 40, multi=
ply by 9/5, then subtract 40<br>
Fahrenheit to Celsius: &nbsp; Add 40, multiply by 5/9, then subtract 40</di=
v>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Convert 10=C2=B0 Celsius <i>(A cool day)</i> to Fahrenheit</h=
3>=20

	<ul>=20
		<li><b>10</b>+40 <em>=3D</em> 50</li>=20
		<li>50=C3=979/5 <em>=3D</em> 90</li>=20
		<li>90=E2=88=9240 <em>=3D</em> <b>50=C2=B0 F</b></li>=20
	</ul>=20
	</div>
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<h3>Quick, but <b>Not Accurate</b></h3> =09

<div class=3D"def center large">Celsius to Fahrenheit: &nbsp; Double, then =
add 30<br>
Fahrenheit to Celsius: &nbsp; Subtract 30, then halve</div>
<div class=3D"simple"></div>
<p>Examples =C2=B0C =E2=86=92 =C2=B0F:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><b>0=C2=B0 C</b> =E2=86=92 0+30 =E2=86=92 <b>30=C2=B0 F</b> (low by 2=
=C2=B0)</li>=20
	<li><b>10=C2=B0 C</b> =E2=86=92 20+30 =E2=86=92 <b>50=C2=B0 F</b> (exact!)=
</li>=20
	<li><b>30=C2=B0 C</b> =E2=86=92 60+30 =E2=86=92 <b>90=C2=B0 F</b> (high by=
 4=C2=B0)</li>=20
	<li><b>180=C2=B0 C</b> =E2=86=92 360+30 =E2=86=92 <b>390=C2=B0 F</b> (high=
 by 34=C2=B0, not good)</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Examples =C2=B0F =E2=86=92 =C2=B0C:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><b>40=C2=B0 F</b> =E2=86=92 10/2 =E2=86=92 <b>5=C2=B0 C</b> (almost ri=
ght)</li>=20
	<li><b>80=C2=B0 F</b> =E2=86=92 50/2 =E2=86=92 <b>25=C2=B0 C</b> (low by a=
bout 2=C2=B0)</li>=20
	<li><b>120=C2=B0 F</b> =E2=86=92 90/2 =E2=86=92 <b>45=C2=B0 C</b> (low by =
about 4=C2=B0)</li>=20
	<li><b>450=C2=B0 F</b> =E2=86=92 420/2 =E2=86=92 <b>210=C2=B0 C</b> (low b=
y about 22=C2=B0, not good)</li>=20
</ul>=20
